EXPERIMENT NO : 3
Title : Java classes,objects and methods 

Code:
package labmanual;
import java.util.Scanner;

class Rectangle {
    String color;
    double area;

    // Constructor 1: Initialize using area
    Rectangle(double area, String colour) {
        this.area = area;
        this.color = colour;
    }

    double get_area() {     // return area
        return area;
    }

    String get_color() {    // return color
        return color;
    }
}

public class Experiment3 {
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        // Input for first rectangle
        System.out.println("Enter details for first rectangle:");
        System.out.print("Area: ");
        double area1 = sc.nextDouble();
        sc.nextLine();  // Consume newline
        System.out.print("Colour: ");
        String colour1 = sc.nextLine();

        // Input for second rectangle
        System.out.println("\nEnter details for second rectangle:");
        System.out.print("Area: ");
        double area2 = sc.nextDouble();
        sc.nextLine();  // Consume newline
        System.out.print("Colour: ");
        String colour2 = sc.nextLine();

        // Create objects
        Rectangle r1 = new Rectangle(area1, colour1);
        Rectangle r2 = new Rectangle(area2, colour2);

        // Compare area and color
        if (r1.get_area() == r2.get_area() && r1.get_color().equalsIgnoreCase(r2.get_color())) {
            System.out.println("\nSame Rectangles");
        } else {
            System.out.println("\nDifferent Rectangles");
        }

        sc.close();
    }
}

OUTPUT:
Enter details for first rectangle:
Area: 50
Colour: Pink

Enter details for second rectangle:
Area: 40
Colour: Pink

Different Rectangles

Enter details for first rectangle:
Area: 20
Colour: red

Enter details for second rectangle:
Area: 59
Colour: purple

Different Rectangles

Enter details for first rectangle:
Area: 30
Colour: blue

Enter details for second rectangle:
Area: 30
Colour: blue

Same Rectangles




Time Complexity: O(n), because equalsIgnoreCase may compare up to n characters of the color strings (n = length of string). All other operations are O(1).
Space Complexity: O(n), for storing the two input strings (n = total length of both).
Worst Case Scenario: When the two color strings are long and nearly identical (or identical), equalsIgnoreCase compares every character, taking O(n) time.

